Gradient Descent¶

This is the blogpost for introducing the lecture 13 of October 18th on the topic of Gradient Descent.

Simple Gradient Descent¶

Previously we have learned some concepts of machine lerning functions like linear reression and logistic regression. What remains is how we can get the minimum of $\theta$ for a function $f(\theta)$. Therefore, the goal of gradient descent is to find a $\theta^*$ such that $f(\theta^*) = \min_{\theta} f(\theta)$.

The following describe the general algorithm of the solutions for it:

  • start from initial guess $\theta^0$ and a learning rate $\alpha$
  • update $\theta^{i+1} \leftarrow \theta^i - \alpha\frac{df(\theta)}{d\theta}$
  • repeat until change in $\theta$ is small, or a maximum number of steps is reached

The following illustration shows how minimum is reached through updating $\theta$ with the learning rate in one parameter.

More complicated Gradient Descent¶

Gradient descent with multiple parameters follows a similar idea. The difference is that now $\theta$ is not a single parameter anymore, but it becomes a vector with multiple parameters. Our goal then becomes $\min_{\theta_1,\theta_2,...,\theta_n} f(\theta_1,\theta_2,...,\theta_n)$. We also need the gradient vector of f, which is the partial derivative of f with respect to the variables respectively.

The following describe the general algorithm of the solutions for multiple parameters:

  • start from initial guess $\vec{\theta}^0$ and a learning rate $\alpha$
  • update $\vec{\theta}^{i+1} \leftarrow \vec{\theta}^i - \alpha\nabla f(\vec{\theta})$, where the $\nabla f(\vec{\theta})$ is the gradient vector and is $(\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial \theta_1},\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial \theta_2},...,\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial \theta_n})$
  • repeat until change in $\theta$ is small, or a maximum number of steps is reached

The following illustration shows how local minimum is reached through updating $\theta$ with the learning rate in multiple parameters.

Gradient Descent for Machine Learning¶

The gradient descent algorithm for machine learning in general is just adding a $D$ to the function where $D$ is the loss function. For example, for linear regression, $D$ is $(X^T\theta - Y)^2$, other parts are pretty much the same.

The following describe the general algorithm of the solutions for multiple parameters:

  • start from initial guess $\vec{\theta}^0$ and a learning rate $\alpha$
  • update $\vec{\theta}^{i+1} \leftarrow \vec{\theta}^i - \alpha\nabla f(\vec{\theta}, D)$
  • repeat until change in $\theta$ is small, or a maximum number of steps is reached

Problem of Gradient Descent¶

Note, I mentioned "local" minimum can be reached in the illustration for gradient descent of multiple parameters above. This has a reason.

It is because by simply doing the above algorithms, the absolute minimum is not guaranteed. We can only find the local minimum in both linear and multi-dimentional gradient descent. Therefore, we would need other methods for achieving finding an absolute minimum.

Solutions¶

One of the solution is called Stochstic Gradient Descent (SGD). In this method, only single or several datapoints $d$ from teh whole datasets $D$ is sampled and used. That way, the $\theta$ will not move as linear as before. It would go through more space for finding minimum.

The following illustration shows the differences of the paths between SGD and Gradient Descent. Rather than going on the tangent line each time, SGD goes around more.


Another Solution is Momentum. In this method, $\beta$ is a number between 0 and 1 that is added before the speed, so that it makes sure not to change the speed too much or too fast. It is called momentum so we can think of it just like how momentum works. $\theta$ moves just like a ball. It bounces further to explore whether there is a lower number away.

Of course, there are also other methods to deal with the problem of funding a global maximum. These solutions also have different drawbacks and advantages, such as efficiency. Which one method to use needs some background and subjective determinations.
